<br>
12) You can also type /d instead of /dir. <br>
<br>
Important note: If you /release, you cannot be ressurrected. <br>
<br>
If you type /bind while not near a bindstone, it will display your current bind point. <br>
<br>
And, /quit sometimes takes more than 20 seconds; most notably, when you have just finished a combat. <br>
<br>
Lastly, a tip from Bolrus: <br>
<br>
No matter what your class, the very first thing you should purchase is a new weapon. As quickly as possible. <br>
<br>
Have fun. <br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ <br>
<br>
Well I would say do tasks and quests for easy leveling. <br>
<br>
Upgrade your weapon immediately once you have a few silver. Toss away the practice weapon. <br>
<br>
Also get cheap armor and shields asap. <br>
<br>
Fight blue and green enemies for safe experience. <br>
<br>
Play solo for more cash and group for easy, safe experience. <br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ <br>
<br>
<br>
the 'C' key is mapped to make your sit or stand depending on your current state. It's a lot faster and easier then the /sit or /stand commands. <br>
<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ <br>
<br>
If you screw up and lose your practice weapon for some odd reason, you can get another one free from your trainer. <br>
<br>
Numlock by default is your autorun key. <br>
<br>
before pressing the PLAY button on the character screen, go to options and look/change the keyboard layout to your liking. For those coming from EQ, changing the mouselook(camera, forget what it's called) option to the right mouse button. I think the default is m. <br>
<br>
Upgrade to a bronze weapon ASAP. practice weapons are okay but you want a good weapon of the type you plan on training. It's a good idea to train 1 point (for the melee classes) in the weapon type of your choice (slashing, crushing/thrust) as soon as you get to level 2 so you can get the initial weapon style. this style typically adds 2 to 3 points of extra damage every time you use it (as long as your endurance holds out). <br>
<br>
Humanoid monsters (skeletons, zombies, goblins, etc.) tend to drop better loot, like pitted weapons, tattered armor and sometimes coin. Easy way to get that starter equipment. Go hunt those mobs when you can but don't ignore other easy mobs (they drop loot too). Getting the first 4 levels is easy. Concentrate on getting money for a better weapon and some decent armor. <br>
<br>
For casters, remember, until you get the quick cast skill, casting in combat is near impossible. So, target a blue or green con mob at maximum distance, nuke nuke nuke until it gets in to melee range and then melee it until you or it dies. You should still get a better weapon ASAP. Just like melees since your starter weapon sucks. <br>
<br>
For the first 5 levels, you don't lose anything when you die so, don't run if it gets dicey. You have nothing to lose and might win. <br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ <br>
<br>
Oh yeah, the quickbar. You can delete buttons off of your quickbar by SHIFT + Right Clicking on the button. <br>
<br>
To rearrange buttons on the bar, pick up a button from your character sheet or make a macro button (i.e. /macro /stand). That will put a button on your cursor. Now you can rearrange the buttons on your quickbar without having to delete and replace the buttons. It works kinda like musical chairs, you move the buttons by replacing the button you want moved with the one your just made and then moving that button to the new spot you want, etc. etc. In the end, if you have a full bar, after you have rearranged the buttons you wanted to move, you should have that original button on your cursor. left click in the game window itself to "drop" that button and return the cursor to normal. <br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ <br>
<br>
Agreeing with that fella further up, quick sell is Shift-S. Just click on the item and hit Shift-S. <br>
<br>
Also, in Albion, instead of buying a new weapon you can kill spriggarns till you get some flint. Hand that into a stonemason and you can get a new weapon (depending on the type of flint). Easy quest and the weapon will last you till your level 5 or so. <br>
<br>
The only problem is killing a spriggarn (which are around level 3 I think) with your crappy newbie weapon. Not easy for some classes =P <br>
<br>
Skellys, Zombies and other undead types may be good for equiping yourself with newbie armor and they drop a few coins. But ultimatly other baddies drop better selling loot. That armor will only sell for a few copper. Stuff like pelts, tusks, heads and skins sell for around 20 - 70 copper. <br>
<br>
And my last tip: Be cheap! Save every penny, silver, copper etc. You will need it. Especially if your a fighter class. <br>
<br>
(And for friars - you should be aiming at around 33 silver when you hit level 5. Thats for a good staff you can get in cotswold that should be yellow to you.) <br>
<br>
Hmm, I'm done. <br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ <br>
<br>
A few more points to make ... <br>
<br>
* When you create you character, don't put any more than 10 points in any one skill. You are penalized for each extra point added. <br>
<br>
* If you can afford it, keep a blunt weapon (as in mace) and a sword on you. Many of the mobs are protected against some types of weapons and/or take extra damage from a certain type. For example, skellies take extra damage from blunt weapons. You will see this as you hit them; (+#) or (-#) is put on each hit. <br>
<br>
* As mentioned, upgrade from your newbie weapon ASAP. This can't be stressed enough. It usually takes about 3-4 silver pieces to do this. <br>
<br>
* Don't allocate any of your skill points until you get to level 5 when you pick your final class. This way, if you change your mind on the class you want, you can do so without wasting points. <br>
<br>
* Make a hotkey for the Sprint Command ... everyone has this skill at level 1. It will allow you to outrun many of the mobs you encounter at the expense your Endurance. <br>
<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ <br>
<br>
Right click on each tab and make sure you turn the messages on for everything. Once you are comfortable, you can customize it a little, but A LOT of players were missing messages because they were on the wrong tab. <br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ <br>
